metadata.name: Concordance #28
metadata.description:
"Concordance" is a study of color relationships in a grid structure. The sketch starts with a simple pallet. Then each color is "lerped" to get levels of transition between the colors. Each color of this newly expanded pallet walks over a grid of cells to simulate rows or columns of gradients. 

Built with p5.js 

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Possible Ways #80
metadata.description:
This project is written in javascript without using any other libraries, and it is an endless real-time software animation.

The appearance of each token is initially determined by the hash, but the size and positions of its elements change randomly over time, creating an infinite performance.

While working on this project, I was inspired by the elusiveness of the moment, that cannot be saved or predicted. It can only be experienced.

Our skies in the next 30 years as temperatures are intensifying and we experience, in the present, unprecedent heat waves. 

Inspired in polaroid images. Each output represents an image, a collectible and a document of perpetual suns. 

Each image showcases a random date and time in the next 30 years.

Oftentimes we will see how the suns try to breach the borders of the polaroid. They seldom manage to completely invade the frame.

Press “s” to save a png image.
Press “h” to save a high resolution: 5500 x 3660 or 3660 x 5500 png frame.

metadata.name: z-pattern : stacked noise #2
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of pattern interferences that can happen in depth perception.

Each token is composed of 35 frames stacked in the z-axis. Each frame is a simple noise field with several detail levels displayed on transparent background.

The 3D stack is oriented at random for each token.

This work is interactive : you can press and drag your mouse around the canvas to explore different views and see several patterns.
